                  <td width="560" valign="top" bgcolor="#C4EECE" class="style2"><p class="style79"><strong><em>It's my party, and I won't cry if I (don't) want  to:</em></strong><em>&nbsp; The  continuing UWB standards war took a new twist this month as Freescale, the  Motorola spin-off that formed one of the two rival organizations that led a  IEEE working group to give up on setting a standard&hellip;quit its own organization,  giving the scribes much to write about.&nbsp;  At the same time, the Bluetooth SIG plighted its troth to the specification  offered by the rival group.&nbsp; Is that the  end of the road for Freescale?&nbsp;  &quot;Just a flesh wound,&quot; according to Calvin Harrison, a  spokesperson for Freescale, sounding rather like the steadily diminishing  knight in Monty Python's Spamalot.</em></p>                      </td>
