                <tr>
                  <td width="560" valign="top" bgcolor="#C4EECE" class="style2"><p class="style79"><strong><em>Nobody ever said that this would be easy:</em></strong><em>&nbsp; It's now been almost a year since I did an  in-depth <a href="http://www.consortiuminfo.org/bulletins/jun05.php#feature">interview  with Tim Berners-Lee</a> focusing on the challenges of rolling out the Semantic  Web.&nbsp; Since then, two things haven't  changed.&nbsp; The first is that it's still  hard to explain the Semantic Web to the world in order to get them on the bus,  as noted in the first article below.&nbsp;  And the second is that those that &quot;get&quot; the Semantic Web the  best and are most motivated to implement it are those dealing with specific  domains of data that they wish to share with others in the same discipline, as  demonstrated by the next two articles.&nbsp;  The fourth and final article below shows that other, and different,  efforts to bring greater order to the ever-exploding volume of data on the Web  are also ongoing.</em></p></td>
                </tr>
