              <p align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p class="style2"><strong><a href="http://technology.guardian.co.uk/weekly/story/0,,1747327,00.html" target="_hdl">Spread the word, and join it up</a></strong><br>
                <strong>The Guardian.com.uk April 7, 2006</strong>&nbsp;...The system that should  revolutionise online searching is the &quot;semantic web&quot;, where online  data is marked up with indications of its meaning, rather than simply its  appearance and links, as currently happens on the world wide web....Sir Tim  Berners-Lee - better known as the inventor of the world wide web - also  originated the idea of the semantic web, which he calls &quot;the web of  data&quot;. But this new brainchild is finding it much harder to take off. <a href="http://technology.guardian.co.uk/weekly/story/0,,1747327,00.html">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.heise.de/english/newsticker/news/71954" target="_hdl">Vikings set out to conquer Semantic Web</a></strong><br>
                <strong>Heise Online.de April 13, 2006</strong>&nbsp;German scientists are working on a  project they call Wikinger (German for &quot;Viking&quot;) based on the concept  of Wikipedia to provide virtual knowledge networking in addition to the classic  exchange of knowledge at Congresses. The goal of the project is to create a  domain-neutral platform for scientists to allow them to perform research in  knowledge bases regardless of where they are and to generate new knowledge via  the Internet in collaboration. To this end, techniques from the Semantic Web  are being used. <a href="http://www.heise.de/english/newsticker/news/71954">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style2"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.bio-itworld.com/newsitems/2006/april/04-10-06-news-sematic-web" target="_hdl">Spearheading the Semantic Web</a></strong><br>
                <strong>Catherine Varmazis</strong><br>
                <strong>BIO-ITWorld.com April 10, 2006</strong>&nbsp;BOSTON &ndash; Sharing their passion for  the Semantic Web at the Bio-IT World Life Sciences Conference + Expo session on  Tuesday were several prominent leaders of the movement. Providing a clinical  perspective was Tonya Hongsermeier of Partners Healthcare, who said the  Semantic Web is necessary for knowledge management because &ldquo;the market is  balking at healthcare inflation.&rdquo; She said eight datapoints are now kept for  each patient (age, height, weight, etc.), but with new tests and personalized  medicine, the number could balloon to 3000. The Semantic Web can reduce the  cost and liability of knowledge management, said Hongsermeier, and is a  critical component of translational medicine going forward. <a href="http://www.bio-itworld.com/newsitems/2006/april/04-10-06-news-sematic-web">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style2"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.fcw.com/article92807-04-03-06-Print" target="_hdl">Framework could aid global information exchange</a></strong><br>
                <strong>Aliya Sternstein</strong><br>
                <strong>FCW.com April 4, 2006</strong>&nbsp;An open-standards group has created a  framework that could facilitate the global exchange of information among  organizations. The naming system could benefit a wide range of disciplines,  from disaster response to medical research. The Open Group&rsquo;s Universal Data  Element Framework (UDEF) has the potential to hasten information exchange by  indexing the world&rsquo;s datasets &mdash; from e-commerce services to government  registries and medical research databases &mdash; in one universally shared semantic  repository. <a href="http://www.fcw.com/article92807-04-03-06-Print">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://news.com.com/2100-1032_3-6060741.html" target="_hdl">Google unveils Web-based calendar app</a></strong><br>
                  <strong>Elinor Mills</strong><br>
                  <strong>CNET.News.com April 13, 2006</strong>&nbsp;The beta version of Google Calendar,  which can be accessed without a Gmail account, enables users to search for and  add events from within the program or through Web sites that use open standards  for calendars. Such sites are invited to add Google Calendar buttons next to  events they list....The application interoperates with other calendaring  programs that use Apple Computer's iCal or XML standards....the company is  opening up the application programming interface so that outside developers can  use it to build third-party programs that will work with Google Calendar data,  ... <a href="http://news.com.com/2100-1032_3-6060741.html">...Full Story</a></p>
              <p align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.iht.com/articles/2006/04/05/business/software.php" target="_hdl">Sharing Lego blocks: Modular software  reshapes the computing landscape</a></strong><br>
                <strong>John Markoff</strong><br>
                <strong>The New York Times April 7, 2006</strong>&nbsp;The Internet is entering its Lego  era. Blocks of interchangeable software components are proliferating on the  Web, and developers are joining them together to create a potentially infinite  array of useful new programs. This new software represents a marked departure  from the inflexible, at times unwieldy, programs of the past, which were  designed to run on individual computers <a href="http://www.iht.com/articles/2006/04/05/business/software.php">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
